{"rawJson":null,"m_plot":"Three amateur actors in theater are chased away by their performance, because the satirically subject from their complaint treates in a controversial manner the cruelty of the Nazis. The three actors take refuge in a rural country where they, having the bright idea to recite a sacred drama on the birth of Jesus Christ, have to interpret the three Biblical Magi. The show is so successful and magically the villagers give birth to a son on Christmas Eve for every family, and there the faith in Jesus is regained.","m_cast":"Silvio Orlando: Melchiorre | Rolf Zacher: \"Augusto\"/ Gaspare | Patrick Bauchau: Baldassarre | Gastone Moschin: Don Gregorio | Laura Betti: Chorus girl | Franco Citti: Attore | Ninetto Davoli: Comparsa","m_reception":null,"m_production":null,"m_sequel":null,"m_based_on":null,"m_directed_by":"Sergio Citti","m_produced_by":null,"m_screenplay_by":null,"m_story_by":"Pier Paolo Pasolini","m_starring":"Silvio Orlando, Franco Citti, Ninetto Davoli, Gastone Moschin","m_music_by":"Ennio Morricone","m_cinematography":"Franco Di Giacomo","m_edited_by":"Ugo De Rossi","m_production_company":null,"m_distributed_by":null,"m_release_dates":"1996","m_running_time":"130 min","m_country":"Italy","m_language":"Italian | I magi randagi, internationally released as We Free Kings, is a 1996 Italian comedy film directed by Sergio Citti.[1][2] | The film won the Silver Ribbon for Best Original Story.[3] |  | ","m_budget":null,"m_box_office":null,"m_marketing":null,"m_reference":"^ Roberto Chiti; Enrico Lancia; Roberto Poppi. Dizionario del cinema italiano: I Film. Gremese Editore, 2002. ISBN 8884401372.  | ^ Maurizio De Benedictis. Sergio Citti. Lo \"straniero\" del cinema italiano. Lithos, 2008. ISBN 8889604379.  | ^ Enrico Lancia. I premi del cinema. Gremese Editore, 1998. ISBN 8877422211.  | ^ Time Out New York, 4–11 December 1997, p. 83.","m_external_link":"We Free Kings at the Internet Movie Database | ","m_poster":"https://upload.wikimedia.or